725238f-a.text:
Thirty-fifth Ave., at the N.W. corner of Linden Street, showing the Redwood Homestead, which stood originally at 7E-76 0rove Street, near Main Street. It later became the home of Benjamin W. Downing who was a school teacher who studied law in his spare time, subsequently opening his office at probably 112 Broadway. He was District Attorney of Queens County in 1864 and for many years thereafter. He was also a Village Trustee and a member of the Board of Education for twenty years,of which he was also at one time president. He moved from Flushing in 1882. This building was moved to this location between 1865 and 1870. In 1922
it was the Jefferson Demooratic Club.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
